problem:
The table shows some of the results of a survey by radio station KAMC. What percentage of the males surveyed listen to the station? [asy]
size(3inch, 1.5inch);
draw((0,0)--(7,0)--(7,2.5)--(0,2.5)--cycle);

label(scale(.75)*"Listen", (2.5, 2), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Don't Listen", (4.5, 2), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Total", (6.35, 2), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Male", (1, 1.33), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Female", (1, .66), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Total", (1, 0), N);
draw((1.75,0)--(1.75,2.5));
draw((3.25,0)--(3.25,2.5));
draw((5.75,0)--(5.75,2.5));
draw((0,.6)--(7,.6));
draw((0,1.2)--(7,1.2));
draw((0,1.8)--(7,1.8));
label(scale(.75)*"?", (2.5, 1.33), N);
label(scale(.75)*"58", (2.5, .66), N);
label(scale(.75)*"136", (2.5, 0), N);

label(scale(.75)*"26", (4.5, 1.33), N);
label(scale(.75)*"?", (4.5, .66), N);
label(scale(.75)*"64", (4.5, 0), N);

label(scale(.75)*"?", (6.35, 1.33), N);
label(scale(.75)*"96", (6.35, .66), N);
label(scale(.75)*"200", (6.35, 0), N);
[/asy]

solution:
Because $200-96=104$ of those surveyed were male, $104-26=78$ of those surveyed are male listeners. [asy]
size(3inch, 1.5inch);
draw((0,0)--(7,0)--(7,2.5)--(0,2.5)--cycle);

label(scale(.75)*"Listen", (2.5, 2), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Don't Listen", (4.5, 2), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Total", (6.35, 2), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Male", (1, 1.33), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Female", (1, .66), N);
label(scale(.75)*"Total", (1, 0), N);
draw((1.75,0)--(1.75,2.5));
draw((3.25,0)--(3.25,2.5));
draw((5.75,0)--(5.75,2.5));
draw((0,.6)--(7,.6));
draw((0,1.2)--(7,1.2));
draw((0,1.8)--(7,1.8));
label(scale(.75)*"78", (2.5, 1.33), N, red);
label(scale(.75)*"58", (2.5, .66), N);
label(scale(.75)*"136", (2.5, 0), N);

label(scale(.75)*"26", (4.5, 1.33), N);
label(scale(.75)*"38", (4.5, .66), N, red);
label(scale(.75)*"64", (4.5, 0), N);

label(scale(.75)*"104", (6.35, 1.33), N, red);
label(scale(.75)*"96", (6.35, .66), N);
label(scale(.75)*"200", (6.35, 0), N);
[/asy] The percentage of males surveyed who listen to KAMC is $\frac{78}{104} \times 100\% =\boxed{75\%}$.
